**HostSideProxyArchitecture**
- Decision: Run LLM CLI proxy on host machine (not in Docker) to access local CLI tools, expose via fixed port (12435) for Docker containers
- Rationale: CLI tools like claude and copilot require host-side authentication and credentials that are difficult to share into containers. Proxy pattern keeps credentials secure on host while providing standardized HTTP API
- Example: `// Server binds to localhost only, Docker accesses via host.docker.internal
const PORT = 12435;
const HOST = '127.0.0.1';
app.listen(PORT, HOST);
// Docker usage: http://host.docker.internal:12435/api/complete`
- Tradeoffs: Pro: Secure credential management - API keys never leave host; Pro: No need to rebuild containers when CLI tools update; Pro: Consistent interface for heterogeneous CLI tools; Con: Requires host-side service management and monitoring; Con: Adds network hop latency (minimal for localhost); Con: Docker containers depend on host service availability
- Evidence: file: src/server.ts:1-8 - Architecture documentation comment, file: src/server.ts:59-60 - Port configuration
